1475–1573":"1475–1573","1500–1554":"1500–1554","1460–1543":"1460–1543","1460–Female":"1460–Deceased","October 1573":"October 1573","1473":"1473","Abt 1500":"about 1500","after 20 September 1573":"after 20 September 1573","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1475":"1475","1573":"1573","Bef 5 April 1554":"before 5 April 1554","1549":"1549","East Bergholt, Suffolk, England":"East Bergholt, Suffolk, England","England":"England","East Bergholt, Babergh district, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","East Bergholt, Babergh district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"East Bergholt, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hedge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a hedge or enclosure, from Middle English <i>hegge</i> ‘hedge, fence’. In the early Middle Ages, hedges were not merely dividers between fields, but had an important defensive function when planted around a settlement or enclosure.","English: probably also a variant of   Hatch  , with voicing of the final consonant.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Hecke  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatch","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hatch (Bedfordshire, Devon, Hampshire, Somerset, Wiltshire), Hacche in South Molton (Devon), or else a topographic name from residence near a hatch, a gate leading to a forest or sometimes a sluice-gate, from Middle English <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>hæcce</i>, Kentish Old English <i>hec(c)</i>). This name has been in Ireland since the 17th century, associated with County Meath and the nearby part of Louth."]},{"name":"Hedges","meanings":["English: variant of   Hedge  , from the plural or, with excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Hedger","meanings":["English (southeastern): occupational name from Middle English <i>heg(g)er</i> ‘hedger, a maker or repairer of hedges’, or perhaps in some cases a topographic name for a ‘dweller by the hedge’; compare   Hedge  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":76,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":85,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hedge was born in 1473, in East Bergholt, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Hedge, was 13 and his mother, Bridget, was 14. He had at least 1 son with Johanna Joan Rainsford. He died in October 1573, in East Bergholt, Suffolk, England, at the age of 100."},"et":{"1473–October 1573":"1473–oktoober 1573","1473–1573":"1473–1573","1475–1573":"1475–1573","1500–1554":"1500–1554","1460–1543":"1460–1543","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","October 1573":"oktoober 1573","1473":"1473","Abt 1500":"umbes 1500","after 20 September 1573":"pärast 20. septembrit 1573","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1475":"1475","1573":"1573","Bef 5 April 1554":"enne 5. aprilli 1554","1549":"1549","East Bergholt, Suffolk, England":"East Bergholt, Suffolk, England","England":"England","East Bergholt, Babergh district, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","East Bergholt, Babergh district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"East Bergholt, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1473–October 1573":"1473–lokakuu 1573","1473–1573":"1473–1573","1475–1573":"1475–1573","1500–1554":"1500–1554","1460–1543":"1460–1543","1460–Female":"1460–Kuollut","October 1573":"lokakuu 1573","1473":"1473","Abt 1500":"noin 1500","after 20 September 1573":"20. syyskuuta 1573 jälkeen","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1475":"1475","1573":"1573","Bef 5 April 1554":"ennen vuotta 5. huhtikuuta 1554","1549":"1549","East Bergholt, Suffolk, England":"East Bergholt, Suffolk, England","England":"England","East Bergholt, Babergh district, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","East Bergholt, Babergh district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"East Bergholt, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1473–October 1573":"1473–octobre 1573","1473–1573":"1473–1573","1475–1573":"1475–1573","1500–1554":"1500–1554","1460–1543":"1460–1543","1460–Female":"